What is a deconstructor?

class Account {
public:
    ~Account(void)
};

cards.expl:
- In the header file of Account.hpp inside the class Account, we have:
    typedef Account t;

- That means Account::t is just an alias for Account.

- Create a type alias called accounts_t, 
  which is a std::vector containing Account objects.

- now we can write 
    accounts_t accounts;
  instead of:
    std::vector<Account> accounts;

- A std::vector is a dynamic array — 
  it can grow and shrink automatically as you add or remove elements.

- Example:
      #include <vector>

      std::vector<int> numbers; // an empty list of ints
      numbers.push_back(10);
      numbers.push_back(20);

  Now numbers contains [10, 20].

  ✅ You don’t need to know the size ahead of time.
  ✅ You can loop, access, and modify items easily.

